item.title: Nataxa flavescens
item.dc:creator: chrisl
item.description: Moth found resting on decking of house, where it remained for several days.

item.title: Macrobathra spp.
item.dc:creator: chrisl
item.description: Resting on leaf of juvenile Red Box tree along New Year Dam Track, Brisbane Ranges National Park. Yet to determine to species level. Similar markings to M. euryleuca.

item.title: Oecophoridae spp.
item.dc:creator: chrisl
item.description: Concealer Moth resting on Prostanthera decussata. Possibly a species of Chysonoma.

item.title: Thalaina selenaea
item.dc:creator: chrisl
item.description: With white fringed forewing margin, rather than rusty colour.

item.title: Doratifera oxleyi
item.dc:creator: chrisl
item.description: This is the male of the species, which looks rather dissimilar to the larger female.

item.title: Anthela repleta
item.dc:creator: chrisl
item.description: In photo 2, the moth has laid eggs on the stem of Pultenaea gunnii subsp. tuberculata.

item.title: Epicyme rubropunctaria
item.dc:creator: chrisl

item.title: Mimaglossa nauplialis

item.description: Pyralidae spp. Identification thanks to Darren Carman.

item.title: Cosmodes elegans
item.dc:creator: chrisl
item.description: A rare pale-brown morph of this species.

item.title: Epicoma sp. (1)
item.dc:creator: chrisl
item.description: A species of Epicoma. There were also multiple clusters of eggs on the glass of the windows around the house. They were covered in hair the same colour as the abdominal tuft of the moth.
